# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pyyaml-parsing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] A **configuration file**, also known as **config file**, is a file that stores data used to configure a software system such as an application, a server or an operating system.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] Some applications provide a tool to create, modify, and verify the syntax of their configuration files – sometimes via graphical user interface (GUI).
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] For context, system administrators may be expected to create and modify text config files via a text editor.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] For server processes and operating-system settings, there is often no standard tool, but operating systems may provide graphical interfaces such as YaST or debconf.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] Some computer programs only read their configuration files at startup.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] Others periodically check the configuration files for changes.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] Users can instruct some programs to re-read the configuration files and apply the changes to the current process, or indeed to read arbitrary files as a configuration file.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] There are no definitive standards or strong conventions.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] In general, a config file can have any format.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] The format that applies to a particular system is determined by the design of that system.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] Often, a standardized format is used since it allows for using tools designed for the format even if not designed for the consuming system.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] In particular, general-purpose serialization formats, such as JSON, XML, and YAML, are often used in open-source and platform-neutral software.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] The specifications for these formats are generally publicly available to support wide-spread use.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] The following table compares notable formats used for configuration data.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] The *syntax typing* column indicates whether the syntax supports data types.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] A format has syntax-typing if a value's type is specified by syntax – e.g.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] `true` is a Boolean while `"true"` is a string.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] A format does not have syntax-typing if a value's type is based on semantics – e.g.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] `true` and `"true"` are both Boolean if the parser expects a Boolean.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] Opinions on the value of syntax-typing vary.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] The following are examples of config files organized by the operating systems on which they are commonly used.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] Many different file formats are used on Unix and Unix-like operating systems.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] Even so, there is a strong tradition of using human-editable, plain text formats including simple key–value pair.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] Filename extensions of `.cnf`, `.conf`, `.cfg`, `.cf` or `.ini` are often used.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] Many formats allow comments, in which case, individual settings can be disabled by prepending with the comment character.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] Often the default configuration files contain extensive internal documentation in the form of comments and man files are also typically used to document the format and options available.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] System-wide software often uses configuration files stored in `/etc`, while user applications often use a "dotfile" – a file or directory in the home directory prefixed with a period, which in Unix hides the file or directory from casual listing.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] Since this causes pollution, newer user applications generally make their own folder in the `.config` directory, a standardized subdirectory of the home directory.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] Similar to config files, a run command (rc) shell script can configure a shell session.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] Often, such scripts are named with an `rc` suffix after the consuming program's name such as `.xinitrc`, `.vimrc`, `.bashrc`, `xsane.rc`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] By contrast, IBM's AIX uses an Object Data Manager (ODM) database to store much of its system settings.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] MS-DOS primarily relied on the `CONFIG.SYS` config file, a plain text file with simple key–value pairs (e.g.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] MS-DOS 6 introduced the INI-file format.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] Similar to an rc file, the batch file named `AUTOEXEC.BAT` ran commands on startup.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] Both these files were retained up to Windows 98SE, which still ran on top of MS-DOS.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] DOS applications used a wide variety of individual configuration files, most of them binary, proprietary and undocumented - and there were no common conventions or formats.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] Early Windows operating systems heavily utilized plain-text INI files which served as the primary mechanism to configure the operating system and applications.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] The APIs to read and write from these still exist in Windows, but after 1993, Microsoft began to steer developers away from using INI files and toward storing settings in the registry, a hierarchical database to store configuration settings, which was introduced with Windows NT.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] Later systems use XML and other formats instead of the registry.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] The Property List is the standard configuration file format in macOS (as well as in iOS, NeXTSTEP, GNUstep and Cocoa applications).
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] It uses the filename extension `.plist`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] IBM's OS/2 uses a binary format, also with a .INI suffix, but this differs from the Windows versions.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] It contains a list of lists of untyped key–value pairs.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] Two files control system-wide settings: OS2.INI and OS2SYS.INI.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] Application developers can choose whether to use them or to create a specific file for their applications.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] HarmonyOS and OpenHarmony-based operating systems use JSON config files, named `config.json`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/configuration-file] The platform IDE, DevEco Studio, provides methods for editing `config.json`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/data-structure] In computer science, a **data structure** is a way to organize and store data that is usually chosen for efficient access to data.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/data-structure] More precisely, a data structure is the physical implementation of a data type, including specifications of the data organization and storage format, as well functions or operations for working with this data.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/data-structure] Data structures are closely related to abstract data types (ADTs).
[src:pyyaml-parsing/data-structure] The data structure describes the representation of data in memory and how operations are carried out, while the ADT describes the logical form or algebraic structure of the data type—what operations are allowed and what results they produce—without describing how those operations are implemented.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/data-structure] Some authors do not use the term "abstract data type" and simply refer to the logical and physical forms of the data structure.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/data-structure] Efficient data structures are essential for managing large datasets and are fundamental to algorithm design.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/data-structure] Relational databases commonly use B-tree indice for data retrieval, while compiler implementations usually use hash tables to look up identifiers.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/data-structure] Filesystems and search engines make extensive use of specialized data structures.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/data-structure] Rob Pike has stated that the choice of data structure almost always has a greater impact on efficiency than the choice of algorithm, as the algorithm is often self-evident.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/data-structure] Data structures are used to organize data in both primary memory (RAM) and secondary storage (such as disks).
[src:pyyaml-parsing/data-structure] Implementing a data structure involves writing a set of subroutines—such as insertion, deletion, traversal, or lookup—that create and manipulate instances of that structure.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/data-structure] Data structures can be implemented using a variety of programming languages and techniques.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/data-structure] A data structure corresponds directly to a single concrete implementation, in contrast to an ADT which describes behavior and operations independently of any particular implementation.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/data-structure] There may be multiple concrete data structures for the same ADT, for example a linked list or a resizable array for the list ADT.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/data-structure] As such, the efficiency of a data structure is closely tied to its concrete implementation, and must be evaluated through benchmarks and theoretical simulation.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/data-structure] Data structures generally rely on the ability of a computer to store and access data via memory addresses (as specified by a pointer—a bit string—or more abstractly via references) that can be itself stored in memory and manipulated by the program.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/data-structure] For example, arrays and records store elements in contiguous memory locations, requiring a rigid layout but allowing fast indexed access by computing the address through arithmetic operations.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/data-structure] In contrast, linked data structures (such as linked lists and trees) store addresses of related elements within their structure, enabling flexible memory usage and dynamic resizing.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/data-structure] These different methods of data structuring come with different tradeoffs and are suited to different tasks.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/data-structure] For instance, the contiguous memory allocation in arrays facilitates rapid access and modification operations, leading to optimized performance in sequential data processing scenarios.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/data-structure] There are numerous types of data structures, generally built upon simpler primitive data types.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/data-structure] Most assembly languages and some low-level languages, such as BCPL (Basic Combined Programming Language), lack built-in support for data structures.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/data-structure] On the other hand, many high-level programming languages and some higher-level assembly languages, such as MASM, have special syntax or other built-in support for certain data structures, such as records and arrays.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/data-structure] For example, the C (a direct descendant of BCPL) and Pascal languages support structs and records, respectively, in addition to vectors (one-dimensional arrays) and multi-dimensional arrays.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/data-structure] Most programming languages feature some sort of library mechanism that allows data structure implementations to be reused by different programs.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/data-structure] Modern languages usually come with standard libraries that implement the most common data structures.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/data-structure] Examples are the C++ Standard Template Library, the Java Collections Framework, and the Microsoft .NET Framework.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/data-structure] Modern languages also generally support modular programming, the separation between the interface of a library module and its implementation.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/data-structure] Some provide opaque data types that allow clients to hide implementation details.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/data-structure] Object-oriented programming languages, such as C++, Java, and Smalltalk, typically use classes for this purpose.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/data-structure] Many known data structures have concurrent versions which allow multiple computing threads to access a single concrete instance of a data structure simultaneously.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] A **file format** is the way that information is encoded for storage in a computer file.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] It may describe the encoding at various levels of abstraction including low-level bit and byte layout as well high-level organization such as markup and tabular structure.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] A file format may be standardized (which can be proprietary or open) or it can be an *ad hoc* convention.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Some file formats are designed for very particular types of data: PNG files, for example, store bitmapped images using lossless data compression.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Other file formats, however, are designed for storage of several different types of data: the Ogg format can act as a container for different types of multimedia including any combination of audio and video, with or without text (such as subtitles), and metadata.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] A text file can contain any stream of characters, including possible control characters, and is encoded in one of various character encoding schemes.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Some file formats, such as HTML, scalable vector graphics, and the source code of computer software are text files with defined syntaxes that allow them to be used for specific purposes.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Some file formats have a published specification describing the format and possibly how to verify the correctness of data in that format.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Such a document is not available for every format (sometimes because the format is considered a trade secret, and sometimes because a document was not authored).
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Sometimes, a format is defined *de facto* by the behavior of the program that accesses the file.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] If there is no specification available, a developer might reverse engineer the format by inspecting files in that format or acquire the specification for a fee and by signing a non-disclosure agreement.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Due to the time and money cost of these approaches, file formats with publicly available specifications tend to be supported by more programs.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Patent law (rather than copyright) can be used to protect the intellectual property inherent in a file format.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Although a patent for a file format is not directly permitted under US law, some formats encode data using a patented algorithm.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] For example, prior to 2004, using compression with the GIF file format required the use of a patented algorithm, and though the patent owner did not initially enforce their patent, they later began collecting royalty fees.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] This has resulted in a significant decrease in the use of GIFs, and is partly responsible for the development of the alternative PNG format.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] However, the GIF patent expired in the US in mid-2003, and worldwide in mid-2004.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Both users and applications need to identify a file's format so that the file can be used appropriately.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Generally, the methods for identification vary by operating system, with each approach having its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] One popular method used by many operating systems, including Windows, macOS, CP/M, MS-DOS, VMS, and VM/CMS, is to indicate the format of a file with a suffix of the file name, known as the extension.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] For example, an HTML document is identified by a file name that ends with .html or .htm, and a GIF image by .gif.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] In the now-antiquated FAT file system, file names were limited to eight characters for the base name plus a three-character extension, known as an 8.3 filename.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Due to the prevalence of this naming scheme, many formats still use three-character extensions even though modern systems support longer extensions.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Since there is no standardized list of extensions, more than one format can use the same extension – especially for three-letter extensions since there is a limited number of three-letter combinations.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] This situation can confuse both users and applications.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] One implication of indicating the file type with the extension is that the users and applications can be tricked into treating a file as a different format simply by renaming it.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] For example, an HTML file can be treated as plain text by adding (or changing the existing) extension filename.txt.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Although this strategy is useful, it can be confusing to less technical users who accidentally make a file unusable (or "lose" it).
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] To try to avoid this scenario, Windows and macOS support hiding the extension.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Hiding the extension, however, can create the appearance of multiple files with the same name in the same folder, which is confusing for people.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] For example, an image may be needed both in .eps format (for publishing) and .png format (for web sites) and one might name them with the same base name (for example, CompanyLogo.eps and CompanyLogo.png).
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] With extensions hidden they appear to have the same name: CompanyLogo.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Hiding extensions can also pose a security risk.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] For example, a malicious user could create an executable program with an innocent name such as "Holiday photo.jpg.exe".
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] The ".exe" would be hidden and an unsuspecting user would see "Holiday photo.jpg", which would appear to be a JPEG image, usually unable to harm the machine.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] However, the operating system would still see the ".exe" extension and run the program, which would then be able to cause harm to the computer.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] The same is true with files with only one extension: as it is not shown to the user, no information about the file can be deduced without explicitly investigating the file.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] To further trick users, it is possible to store an icon inside the program, in which case some operating systems' icon assignment for the executable file (.exe) would be overridden with an icon commonly used to represent JPEG images, making the program look like an image.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Extensions can also be spoofed: some Microsoft Word macro viruses create a Word file in template format and save it with a .doc extension.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Since Word generally ignores extensions and looks at the format of the file, these would open as templates, execute, and spread the virus.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] This represents a practical problem for Windows systems where extension-hiding is turned on by default.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] A file's format may be indicated inside the file itself – either as information intended for this purpose or as identifiable data within the format that can be used for identification even though that is not its intended purpose.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Often intentionally placed information is located at the beginning of a file since this is relatively easy to read from a file both by users and applications.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] When the information at the beginning of the file is a structure that contains other metadata, then the structure is often called a *file header*.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] When the file starts with a relatively small datum that only indicates the format, then it is often called a *magic number*.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] The metadata contained in a file header are usually stored at the start of the file, but might be present in other areas too, often including the end, depending on the file format or the type of data contained.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Character-based (text) files usually have character-based headers, whereas binary formats usually have binary headers, although this is not a rule.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Text-based file headers usually take up more space, but being human-readable, they can easily be examined by using simple software such as a text editor or a hexadecimal editor.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] As well as indicating the file format, file headers may contain metadata about the file and its contents.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] For example, most image files store information about image format, size, resolution and color space, and optionally authoring information such as who made the image, when and where it was made, what camera model and photographic settings were used (Exif), and so on.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Such metadata may be used by software reading or interpreting the file during the loading process and afterwards.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] File headers may be used by an operating system to quickly gather information about a file without loading it all into memory, but doing so uses more of a computer's resources than reading directly from the directory information.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] For instance, when a graphic file manager has to display the contents of a folder, it must read the headers of many files before it can display the appropriate icons, but these will be located in different places on the storage medium thus taking longer to access.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] A folder containing many files with complex metadata such as thumbnail information may require considerable time before it can be displayed.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] If a header is binary hard-coded such that the header itself needs complex interpretation in order to be recognized, especially for metadata content protection's sake, there is a risk that the file format can be misinterpreted.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] It may even have been badly written at the source.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] This can result in corrupt metadata which, in extremely bad cases, might even render the file unreadable.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] A more complex example of file headers are those used for wrapper (or container) file formats.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] One way to incorporate file type metadata is to store a "magic number" inside the file itself.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Originally, this term was used for 2-byte identifiers at the start of files, but since any binary sequence can be regarded as a number, any feature of a file format which uniquely distinguishes it can be used for identification.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] GIF images, for instance, always begin with the ASCII representation of either `GIF87a` or `GIF89a`, depending upon the standard to which they adhere.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Many file types, especially plain-text files, are harder to spot by this method.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] HTML files, for example, might begin with the string `<html>` (which is not case sensitive), or an appropriate document type definition that starts with `<!DOCTYPE html`, or, for XHTML, the XML identifier, which begins with `<?xml`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] The files can also begin with HTML comments, random text, or several empty lines, but still be usable HTML.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] The magic number approach offers better guarantees that the format will be identified correctly, and can often determine more precise information about the file.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Also, data must be read from the file itself, increasing latency as opposed to metadata stored in the directory.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Where file types do not lend themselves to recognition in this way, the system must fall back to metadata.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] On the other hand, a valid magic number does not guarantee that the file is not corrupt or is of a correct type.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] So-called shebang lines in script files are a special case of magic numbers.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] There, the magic number consists of human-readable text within the file that identifies a specific interpreter and options to be passed to it.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] This system was then enhanced with the Amiga standard Datatype recognition system.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Another method was the FourCC method, originating in OSType on Macintosh, later adapted by Interchange File Format (IFF) and derivatives.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] A final way of storing the format of a file is to explicitly store information about the format in the file system, rather than within the file itself.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] This approach keeps the metadata separate from both the main data and the name, but is also less portable than either filename extensions or "magic numbers", since the format has to be converted from filesystem to filesystem.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] While this is also true to an extent with filename extensions— for instance, for compatibility with MS-DOS's three character limit— most forms of storage have a roughly equivalent definition of a file's data and name, but may have varying or no representation of further metadata.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Note that zip files and other archive files solve the problem of handling metadata.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] A utility program collects multiple files together along with metadata about each file and the folders/directories they came from all within one new file (e.g. a zip file with extension .zip).
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] The new file is also compressed and possibly encrypted, but now is transmissible as a single file across operating systems by FTP transmissions or sent by email as an attachment.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] At the destination, the single file received has to be unzipped by a compatible utility to be useful.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] The problems of handling metadata are solved this way using zip files or archive files.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] The Mac OS' Hierarchical File System and HFS+ file system, and the Apple File System, store codes for *creator* and *type* as part of the directory entry for each file.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] These codes could be any 4-byte sequence but were often selected so that the ASCII representation formed a sequence of meaningful characters, such as an abbreviation of the application's name or the developer's initials.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] For instance a HyperCard "stack" file has a *creator* of WILD (from Hypercard's previous name, "WildCard") and a *type* of STAK.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] The BBEdit text editor has a creator code of `R*ch` referring to its original programmer, Rich Siegel.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] The type code specifies the format of the file, while the creator code specifies the default program to open it with when double-clicked by the user.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] For example, the user could have several text files all with the type code of TEXT, but each open in a different program, due to having differing creator codes.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] This feature was intended so that, for example, human-readable plain-text files could be opened in a general-purpose text editor, while programming or HTML code files would open in a specialized editor or IDE.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] However, this feature was often the source of user confusion, as which program would launch when the files were double-clicked was often unpredictable.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] RISC OS uses a similar system, consisting of a 12-bit number which can be looked up in a table of descriptions—e.g. the hexadecimal number `FF5` is "aliased" to PoScript, representing a PostScript file.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] A Uniform Type Identifier (UTI) is a method used in macOS for uniquely identifying "typed" classes of entities, such as file formats.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] It was developed by Apple as a replacement for OSType (type & creator codes).
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] The UTI is a Core Foundation string, which uses a reverse-DNS string.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Some common and standard types use a domain called public (e.g. public.png for a Portable Network Graphics image), while other domains can be used for third-party types (e.g. com.adobe.pdf for Portable Document Format).
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] UTIs can be defined within a hierarchical structure, known as a conformance hierarchy.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Thus, public.png conforms to a supertype of public.image, which itself conforms to a supertype of public.data.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] A UTI can exist in multiple hierarchies, which provides great flexibility.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] In IBM OS/VS through z/OS, the VSAM catalog (prior to ICF catalogs) and the VSAM Volume Record in the VSAM Volume Data Set (VVDS) (with ICF catalogs) identifies the type of VSAM dataset.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] In IBM OS/360 through z/OS, a format 1 or 7 Data Set Control Block (DSCB) in the Volume Table of Contents (VTOC) identifies the Dataset Organization (DSORG) of the dataset described by it.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] The HPFS, FAT12, and FAT16 (but not FAT32) filesystems allow the storage of "extended attributes" with files.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] These comprise an arbitrary set of triplets with a name, a coded type for the value, and a value, where the names are unique and values can be up to 64 KB long.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] There are standardized meanings for certain types and names (under OS/2).
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] One such is that the ".TYPE" extended attribute is used to determine the file type.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Its value comprises a list of one or more file types associated with the file, each of which is a string, such as "Plain Text" or "HTML document".
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] The NTFS filesystem also allows storage of OS/2 extended attributes, as one of the file *forks*, but this feature is merely present to support the OS/2 subsystem (not present in XP), so the Win32 subsystem treats this information as an opaque block of data and does not use it.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Instead, it relies on other file forks to store meta-information in Win32-specific formats.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] OS/2 extended attributes can still be read and written by Win32 programs, but the data must be entirely parsed by applications.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] On Unix and Unix-like systems, the ext2, ext3, ext4, ReiserFS version 3, XFS, JFS, FFS, and HFS+ filesystems allow the storage of extended attributes with files.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] These include an arbitrary list of "name=value" strings, where the names are unique and a value can be accessed through its related name.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] The PRONOM Persistent Unique Identifier (PUID) is an extensible scheme of persistent, unique, and unambiguous identifiers for file formats, which has been developed by The National Archives of the UK as part of its PRONOM technical registry service.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] PUIDs can be expressed as Uniform Resource Identifiers using the info:pronom/ namespace.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Although not yet widely used outside of the UK government and some digital preservation programs, the PUID scheme does provide greater granularity than most alternative schemes.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] MIME types are widely used in many Internet-related applications, and increasingly elsewhere, although their usage for on-disc type information is rare.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] These consist of a standardised system of identifiers (managed by IANA) consisting of a *type* and a *sub-type*, separated by a slash—for instance, text/html or image/gif.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] These were originally intended as a way of identifying what type of file was attached to an e-mail, independent of the source and target operating systems.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] MIME types identify files on BeOS, AmigaOS 4.0 and MorphOS, as well as store unique application signatures for application launching.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] In AmigaOS and MorphOS, the Mime type system works in parallel with Amiga specific Datatype system.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] There are problems with the MIME types though; several organizations and people have created their own MIME types without registering them properly with IANA, which makes the use of this standard awkward in some cases.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] File format identifiers are another, not widely used way to identify file formats according to their origin and their file category.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] It was created for the Description Explorer suite of software.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] It is composed of several digits of the form `NNNNNNNNN-XX-YYYYYYY`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] The first part indicates the organization origin/maintainer (this number represents a value in a company/standards organization database), and the 2 following digits categorize the type of file in hexadecimal.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] The final part is composed of the usual filename extension of the file or the international standard number of the file, padded left with zeros.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] For example, the PNG file specification has the FFID of `000000001-31-0015948` where `31` indicates an image file, `0015948` is the standard number and `000000001` indicates the International Organization for Standardization (ISO).
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Another less popular way to identify the file format is to examine the file contents for distinguishable patterns among file types.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] The contents of a file are a sequence of bytes and a byte has 256 unique permutations (0–255).
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Thus, counting the occurrence of byte patterns that is often referred to as byte frequency distribution gives distinguishable patterns to identify file types.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] There are many content-based file type identification schemes that use a byte frequency distribution to build the representative models for file type and use any statistical and data mining techniques to identify file types.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] There are several types of ways to structure data in a file.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] The most usual ones are described below.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Earlier file formats used raw data formats that consisted of directly dumping the memory images of one or more structures into the file.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Unless the memory images also have reserved spaces for future extensions, extending and improving this type of structured file is very difficult.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] It also creates files that might be specific to one platform or programming language (for example a structure containing a Pascal string is not recognized as such in C).
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] On the other hand, developing tools for reading and writing these types of files is very simple.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] The limitations of the unstructured formats led to the development of other types of file formats that could be easily extended and be backward compatible at the same time.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] In this kind of file structure, each piece of data is embedded in a container that somehow identifies the data.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] The container's scope can be identified by start- and end-markers of some kind, by an explicit length field somewhere, or by fixed requirements of the file format's definition.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Throughout the 1970s, many programs used formats of this general kind.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] For example, word-processors such as troff, Script, and Scribe, and database export files such as CSV.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Electronic Arts and Commodore-Amiga also used this type of file format in 1985, with their IFF (Interchange File Format) file format.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] A container is sometimes called a *"chunk"*, although "chunk" may also imply that each piece is small, and/or that chunks do not contain other chunks; many formats do not impose those requirements.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] The information that identifies a particular "chunk" may be called many different things, often terms including "field name", "identifier", "label", or "tag".
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] The identifiers are often human-readable, and classify parts of the data: for example, as a "surname", "address", "rectangle", "font name", etc.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] These are not the same thing as identifiers in the sense of a database key or serial number (although an identifier may well identify its *associated data* as such a key).
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] With this type of file structure, tools that do not know certain chunk identifiers simply skip those that they do not understand.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Depending on the actual meaning of the skipped data, this may or may not be useful (CSS explicitly defines such behavior).
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] This concept has been used again and again by RIFF (Microsoft-IBM equivalent of IFF), PNG, JPEG storage, DER (Distinguished Encoding Rules) encoded streams and files (which were originally described in CCITT X.409:1984 and therefore predate IFF), and Structured Data Exchange Format (SDXF).
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] This is another extensible format, that closely resembles a file system (OLE Documents are actual filesystems), where the file is composed of 'directory entries' that contain the location of the data within the file itself as well as its signatures (and in certain cases its type).
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Good examples of these types of file structures are disk images, executables, OLE documents TIFF, libraries.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Some file formats like ODT and DOCX, being PKZIP-based, are both chunked and carry a directory.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] The structure of a directory-based file format lends itself to modifications more easily than unstructured or chunk-based formats.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] The nature of this type of format allows users to carefully construct files that causes reader software to do things the authors of the format never intended to happen.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/file-format] Directory-based file formats also use values that point at other areas in the file but if some later data value points back at data that was read earlier, it can result in an infinite loop for any reader software that assumes the input file is valid and blindly follows the loop.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] PyYAML is a YAML parser and emitter for Python.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] To install from source, download the source package *PyYAML-5.1.tar.gz* and unpack it.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] If you want to use LibYAML bindings, which are much faster than the pure Python version, you need to download and install LibYAML.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] In order to use LibYAML based parser and emitter, use the classes `CParser` and `CEmitter`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] Note that there are some subtle (but not really significant) differences between pure Python and LibYAML based parsers and emitters.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] It’s a correct output despite the fact that the style of the nested mapping is different.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] By default, PyYAML chooses the style of a collection depending on whether it has nested collections.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] If a collection has nested collections, it will be assigned the block style.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] If you want collections to be always serialized in the block style, set the parameter `default_flow_style` of `dump()` to `False`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] Starting from the *3.08* release, PyYAML and LibYAML bindings provide a complete support for Python 3.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] This is a short outline of differences in PyYAML API between Python 2 and Python 3 versions.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] Start with importing the `yaml` package.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] The function `yaml.load` converts a YAML document to a Python object.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] `yaml.load` accepts a byte string, a Unicode string, an open binary file object, or an open text file object.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] A byte string or a file must be encoded with *utf-8*, *utf-16-be* or *utf-16-le* encoding.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] `yaml.load` detects the encoding by checking the *BOM* (byte order mark) sequence at the beginning of the string/file.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] If no *BOM* is present, the *utf-8* encoding is assumed.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] If a string or a file contains several documents, you may load them all with the `yaml.load_all` function.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] PyYAML allows you to construct a Python object of any type.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] Even instances of Python classes can be constructed using the `!!python/object` tag.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] Note that the ability to construct an arbitrary Python object may be dangerous if you receive a YAML document from an untrusted source such as the Internet.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] The function `yaml.safe_load` limits this ability to simple Python objects like integers or lists.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] A python object can be marked as safe and thus be recognized by `yaml.safe_load`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] To do this, derive it from `yaml.YAMLObject` (as explained in section *Constructors, representers, resolvers*) and explicitly set its class property `yaml_loader` to `yaml.SafeLoader`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] The `yaml.dump` function accepts a Python object and produces a YAML document.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] `yaml.dump` accepts the second optional argument, which must be an open text or binary file.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] In this case, `yaml.dump` will write the produced YAML document into the file.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] Otherwise, `yaml.dump` returns the produced document.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] If you need to dump several YAML documents to a single stream, use the function `yaml.dump_all`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] Python objects to be serialized into a YAML document.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] The second optional argument is an open file.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] You may even dump instances of Python classes.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] `yaml.dump` supports a number of keyword arguments that specify formatting details for the emitter.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] For instance, you may set the preferred intendation and width, use the canonical YAML format or force preferred style for scalars and collections.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] You may define your own application-specific tags.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] `yaml.YAMLObject` uses metaclass magic to register a constructor, which transforms a YAML node to a class instance, and a representer, which serializes a class instance to a YAML node.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] If you don’t want to use metaclasses, you may register your constructors and representers using the functions `yaml.add_constructor` and `yaml.add_representer`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] First we define a representer that converts a dice object to a scalar node with the tag `!dice`, then we register it.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] You might not want to specify the tag `!dice` everywhere.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] There is a way to teach PyYAML that any untagged plain scalar which looks like XdY has the implicit tag `!dice`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] A good introduction to the YAML syntax is Chapter 2 of the YAML specification.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] Note that it is focused on a Ruby implementation and uses the old YAML 1.0 syntax.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] Here we present most common YAML constructs together with the corresponding Python objects.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] YAML stream is a collection of zero or more documents.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] Documents may optionally end with `...`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] A single document may or may not be marked with `---`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] A block sequence may be nested to a block mapping.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] Note that in this case it is not necessary to indent the sequence.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] A plain scalar does not use indicators to denote its start and end, therefore it’s the most restricted style.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] Its natural applications are names of attributes and parameters.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] Using single-quoted scalars, you may express any value that does not contain special characters.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] No escaping occurs for single quoted scalars except that a pair of adjacent quotes `''` is replaced with a lone single quote `'`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] Double-quoted is the most powerful style and the only style that can express any scalar value.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] Using escaping sequences `\x*` and `\u***`, you may express any ASCII or Unicode character.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] There are two kind of block scalar styles: *literal* and *folded*.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] The literal style is the most suitable style for large block of text such as source code.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] The folded style is similar to the literal style, but two adjacent non-empty lines are joined to a single line separated by a space character.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] Using YAML you may represent objects of arbitrary graph-like structures.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] If you want to refer to the same object from different parts of a document, you need to use anchors and aliases.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] Anchors are denoted by the `&` indicator while aliases are denoted by ``.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] expresses the idea of a hero holding a heavy sword in both hands.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] PyYAML now fully supports recursive objects.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] will produce a list object containing a reference to itself.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] Tags are used to denote the type of a YAML node.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] Standard YAML tags are defined at http://yaml.org/type/index.html.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] Plain scalars without explicitly defined tags are subject to implicit tag resolution.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] The scalar value is checked against a set of regular expressions and if one of them matches, the corresponding tag is assigned to the scalar.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] PyYAML allows an application to add custom implicit tag resolvers.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] The following table describes how nodes with different tags are converted to Python objects.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] There are four tags that are converted to `str` and `unicode` values: `!!str`, `!!binary`, `!!python/str`, and `!!python/unicode`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] `!!str`-tagged scalars are converted to `str` objects if its value is *ASCII*.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] `!!binary`-tagged scalars are converted to `str` objects with its value decoded using the *base64* encoding.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] `!!python/str` scalars are converted to `str` objects encoded with *utf-8* encoding.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] `!!python/unicode` scalars are converted to `unicode` objects.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] Conversely, a `str` object is converted to 1. a `!!str` scalar if its value is *ASCII*.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] 2. a `!!python/str` scalar if its value is a correct *utf-8* sequence.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] A `unicode` object is converted to 1. a `!!python/unicode` scalar if its value is *ASCII*.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] In Python 3, `str` objects are converted to `!!str` scalars and `bytes` objects to `!!binary` scalars.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] For compatibility reasons, tags `!!python/str` and `!!python/unicode` are still supported and converted to `str` objects.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p01] In order to represent static Python objects like functions or classes, you need to use a complex `!!python/name` tag.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `scan(stream)` scans the given `stream` and produces a sequence of tokens.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `parse(stream)` parses the given `stream` and produces a sequence of parsing events.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `emit(events, stream=None)` serializes the given sequence of parsing `events` and writes them to the `stream`. if `stream` is `None`, it returns the produced stream.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `compose(stream)` parses the given `stream` and returns the root of the representation graph for the first document in the stream.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] If there are no documents in the stream, it returns `None`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `compose_all(stream)` parses the given `stream` and returns a sequence of representation graphs corresponding to the documents in the stream.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `serialize(node, stream=None)` serializes the given representation graph into the `stream`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] If `stream` is `None`, it returns the produced stream.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `serialize_all(node, stream=None)` serializes the given sequence of representation graphs into the given `stream`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `load(stream)` parses the given `stream` and returns a Python object constructed from for the first document in the stream.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `load_all(stream)` parses the given `stream` and returns a sequence of Python objects corresponding to the documents in the stream.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `safe_load(stream)` parses the given `stream` and returns a Python object constructed from for the first document in the stream.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `safe_load` recognizes only standard YAML tags and cannot construct an arbitrary Python object.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `safe_load_all(stream)` parses the given `stream` and returns a sequence of Python objects corresponding to the documents in the stream.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `safe_load_all` recognizes only standard YAML tags and cannot construct an arbitrary Python object.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `dump(data, stream=None)` serializes the given Python object into the `stream`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `dump_all(data, stream=None)` serializes the given sequence of Python objects into the given `stream`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] Each object is represented as a YAML document.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `safe_dump(data, stream=None)` serializes the given Python object into the `stream`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `safe_dump` produces only standard YAML tags and cannot represent an arbitrary Python object.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `safe_dump_all(data, stream=None)` serializes the given sequence of Python objects into the given `stream`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `safe_dump_all` produces only standard YAML tags and cannot represent an arbitrary Python object.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `add_constructor(tag, constructor)` specifies a `constructor` for the given `tag`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] A constructor is a function that converts a node of a YAML representation graph to a native Python object.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] A constructor accepts an instance of `Loader` and a node and returns a Python object.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `add_multi_constructor(tag_prefix, multi_constructor)` specifies a `multi_constructor` for the given `tag_prefix`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] A multi-constructor is a function that converts a node of a YAML representation graph to a native Python object.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] A multi-constructor accepts an instance of `Loader`, the suffix of the node tag, and a node and returns a Python object.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `add_representer(data_type, representer)` specifies a `representer` for Python objects of the given `data_type`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] A representer is a function that converts a native Python object to a node of a YAML representation graph.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] A representer accepts an instance of `Dumper` and an object and returns a node.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `add_multi_representer(base_data_type, multi_representer)` specifies a `multi_representer` for Python objects of the given `base_data_type` or any of its subclasses.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] A multi-representer is a function that converts a native Python object to a node of a YAML representation graph.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] A multi-representer accepts an instance of `Dumper` and an object and returns a node.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `add_implicit_resolver(tag, regexp, first)` adds an implicit tag resolver for plain scalars.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] If the scalar value is matched the given `regexp`, it is assigned the `tag`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `first` is a list of possible initial characters or `None`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `add_path_resolver(tag, path, kind)` adds a path-based implicit tag resolver.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] A `path` is a list of keys that form a path to a node in the representation graph.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] Paths elements can be string values, integers, or `None`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] The `kind` of a node can be `str`, `list`, `dict`, or `None`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] An instance of `Mark` points to a certain position in the input stream.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `name` is the name of the stream, for instance it may be the filename if the input stream is a file.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `line` and `column` is the line and column of the position (starting from 0).
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `buffer`, when it is not `None`, is a part of the input stream that contain the position and `pointer` refers to the position in the `buffer`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] If the YAML parser encounters an error condition, it raises an exception which is an instance of `YAMLError` or of its subclass.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] An application may catch this exception and warn a user.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] An exception produced by the YAML processor may point to the problematic position.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] They are not really useful except for low-level YAML applications such as syntax highlighting.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `start_mark` and `end_mark` denote the beginning and the end of a token.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] Events are used by the low-level Parser and Emitter interfaces, which are similar to the SAX API.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] While the Parser parses a YAML stream and produces a sequence of events, the Emitter accepts a sequence of events and emits a YAML stream.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] The `flow_style` flag indicates if a collection is block or flow.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] The possible values are `None`, `True`, `False`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] The `style` flag of a scalar event indicates the style of the scalar.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] The `implicit` flag of a collection start event indicates if the tag may be omitted when the collection is emitted.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] The `implicit` flag of a scalar event is a pair of boolean values that indicate if the tag may be omitted when the scalar is emitted in a plain and non-plain style correspondingly.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] Nodes are entities in the YAML informational model.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] There are three kinds of nodes: *scalar*, *sequence*, and *mapping*.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] In PyYAML, nodes are produced by Composer and can be serialized to a YAML stream by Serializer.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] The `style` and `flow_style` flags have the same meaning as for events.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] The value of a scalar node must be a unicode string.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] The value of a sequence node is a list of nodes.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] The value of a mapping node is a list of pairs consisting of key and value nodes.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `Loader(stream)` is the most common of the above classes and should be used in most cases.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] It can be a string, a Unicode string, an open file, an open Unicode file.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `Loader` supports all predefined tags and may construct an arbitrary Python object.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] Therefore it is not safe to use `Loader` to load a document received from an untrusted source.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] By default, the functions `scan`, `parse`, `compose`, `construct`, and others use `Loader`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `SafeLoader(stream)` supports only standard YAML tags and thus it does not construct class instances and probably safe to use with documents received from an untrusted source.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] The functions `safe_load` and `safe_load_all` use `SafeLoader` to parse a stream.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `BaseLoader(stream)` does not resolve or support any tags and construct only basic Python objects: lists, dictionaries and Unicode strings.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `CLoader`, `CSafeLoader`, `CBaseLoader` are versions of the above classes written in C using the LibYAML library.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `Loader.check_token(*TokenClasses)` returns `True` if the next token in the stream is an instance of one of the given `TokenClasses`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `Loader.peek_token()` returns the next token in the stream, but does not remove it from the internal token queue.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] The function returns `None` at the end of the stream.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `Loader.get_token()` returns the next token in the stream and removes it from the internal token queue.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `Loader.check_event(*EventClasses)` returns `True` if the next event in the stream is an instance of one of the given `EventClasses`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `Loader.peek_event()` returns the next event in the stream, but does not remove it from the internal event queue.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `Loader.get_event()` returns the next event in the stream and removes it from the internal event queue.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `Loader.check_node()` returns `True` is there are more documents available in the stream.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `Loader.get_node()` construct the representation graph of the next document in the stream and returns its root node.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `Loader.check_data()` returns `True` is there are more documents available in the stream.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `Loader.get_data()` constructs and returns a Python object corresponding to the next document in the stream.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `Loader.add_constructor(tag, constructor)`: see `add_constructor`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `Loader.add_multi_constructor(tag_prefix, multi_constructor)`: see `add_multi_constructor`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `Loader.construct_scalar(node)` checks that the given `node` is a scalar and returns its value.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] This function is intended to be used in constructors.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `Loader.construct_sequence(node)` checks that the given `node` is a sequence and returns a list of Python objects corresponding to the node items.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `Loader.construct_mapping(node)` checks that the given `node` is a mapping and returns a dictionary of Python objects corresponding to the node keys and values.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `Loader.add_implicit_resolver(tag, regexp, first)`: see `add_implicit_resolver`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `Loader.add_path_resolver(tag, path, kind)`: see `add_path_resolver`.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `Dumper(stream)` is the most common of the above classes and should be used in most cases.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] It can be an open file or an open Unicode file.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] `Dumper` supports all predefined tags and may represent an arbitrary Python object.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] Therefore it may produce a document that cannot be loaded by other YAML processors.
[src:pyyaml-parsing/pyyamldocumentation-p02] By default, the functions `emit`, `serialize`, `dump`, and others use `Dumper`.
